                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Mobs spawn with different magic resists. So while the majority of a certain type of mob may have low MR you can hit one that will resist nearly everything you throw at it. Mez and switch to a different mob if this happens. Knowing what is high mr and what is low MR is very helpful and can mean winning or losing. 
<br />

<br />
Another thing is your level. I know 1 level may not seem like a lot to you as it's lvl 64 vs lvl 65 but that can mean the difference between longer charms and short as all heck charm durations. Remember, most of these mobs are very high level compared to pre-pop charming. Before PoP most charming was done on mobs usually 7-10 levels lower. In PoP most mobs are at most 5 levels lower when using CoD for charming. With increased MR to boot. 
<br />

<br />
Total Domination. I know most question how much it actually helps but even if it helps very little it does help...
<br />

<br />
Try pushing your cha up to about 250-300 to see if that helps. I don't have any gear specifically for cha but I think buffed I'm in the 270'ish range? Not too sure but I know it's below 300. That's without any cha augments or cha specific gear. Although I probably need to pick some up for LDoN hard dungeons, but that's another story. 
<br />

<br />
Get hp and movment buffs before heading in. Sow/SoE and pot9/virtue helps a lot. A good enchanter can do without these buffs but the margin for error becomes ever so much smaller without these buffs. 
<br />

<br />
Most charm soloing is pretty basic in that you use the same skills and spell types regardless of level. I'm not gonna bother doing a charm guide here as there are plenty of good ones written by others already and I'd only be re-hashing the same old info. The biggest thing is practice, practice, practice. Find out what works for you and use it. Not everyone charm solos the same way. For instance, most people use WoM but I rarely use it when charm soloing. A lot of times I won't even have it up.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
